Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Coronavirus (COVID-19): stay up to date
Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Kyrgyzstan. See information on measures introduced in Kyrgyzstan to limit the spread of the virus. Find out how to return to the UK from Kyrgyzstan.
See coronavirus travel advice for guidance on international travel.
Sign up for email alerts for Kyrgyzstan travel advice.
The Kyrgyzstan authorities have declared a state of emergency and introduced a number of precautionary measures, including a ban on foreign nationals entering the country and a curfew in major cities between 9pm and 6am. See Coronavirus
There are currently no commercial flight options scheduled to leave Kyrgyzstan. This travel advice will be updated when further options for leaving Kyrgyzstan become available. See Return to the UK
Terrorist attacks in Kyrgyzstan can’t be ruled out. You should be vigilant in public places and follow security advice from the local authorities. See Terrorism.
Take care if you travel to the Oblasts (Provinces) of Osh, Batken and Jalal-Abad. See Local travel
All land borders are currently closed in response to the outbreak of coronavirus (COVID-19), except for transit of key goods. You should follow local government announcements and media reporting for updates on opening and additional security procedures.
Skirmishes can occur along the disputed Kyrgyz-Tajik border. Previous incidents have involved both civilians and border guards and several have involved firearms. There are also occasional security incidents on the Kyrgyz/Uzbek and Kyrgyz/Kazakh borders. There’s a risk of further localised violence and border closures at any time. You should remain vigilant in border areas and check local media reports before you travel. See Local travel
The Kazakh / Kyrgyz border is currently closed. You should also be aware that Kazakhstan has introduced new visa requirements. See the Visas Section of Travel Advice for Kazakhstan for more information.
There is a high risk of earthquakes. See Natural Disasters
You must carry your passport, or a notarised copy of it, at all times. See Local laws and customs
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
